                        At 60, Carol Thompson found herself homeless on the cold streets of Salt Lake City. Once a school secretary living a quiet life in Ogden, everything changed after a cancer diagnosis. The medical bills left her broke, her home foreclosed, and with no family to turn to, she ended up on the streets. Utah winters were unforgiving, and after three years, Carol’s health was failing as she struggled to stay warm in freezing temperatures.

                        One November evening, volunteers from the Turtle Shelter Organization handed Carol a "high-tech portable warmth vest." The lightweight vest, made from advanced thermal materials, retained heat in temperatures as low as -10°F and was powered by a rechargeable battery. That night, for the first time in years, Carol slept through the cold without shivering.

                        The vest gave Carol more than warmth—it gave her a renewed sense of hope. With fewer daily struggles to stay warm, she connected with local housing programs and secured a small room for the winter. Inspired by the help she received, Carol began volunteering at a food pantry, slowly rebuilding her life. The vest wasn’t just clothing; it was the start of a second chance, proving to Carol that even in the coldest of times, warmth and compassion can pave the way forward.
